5. HTTP REQUEST AND RESPONSE (IMPORTANT FOR BACKEND)

HTTP Request:

Contains two parts:

1. Headers:
- URL/URI
- Method (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE)
- Content-Type (JSON, text, image, video, PDF)
- Authentication token
- IP address
- Date/time

2. Body:
- JSON data
- Form data
- Text data

---

HTTP Response:

Contains two parts:

1. Headers:
- Content-Type
- Content-Length
- Status Code
- Server info

2. Body:
- JSON response
- HTML response
- Text response

---

HTTP STATUS CODES:

1xx -> Informational
2xx -> Success (200 OK)
3xx -> Redirection
4xx -> Client error (404 Not Found)
5xx -> Server error

---

6. REST vs SOAP (VERY IMPORTANT)

REST:
- Works on HTTP protocol
- Lightweight
- Uses JSON (mostly)
- Easy to integrate
- Faster performance
- Stateless communication

SOAP:
- Uses XML format
- Heavy compared to REST
- More secure but complex
- Requires strict standards

Conclusion:
REST is widely used in modern applications.

---

7. JSON (JavaScript Object Notation)

JSON is a lightweight data format used to transfer data between client and server.

Structure:
Key-value pair format

Example:
{
  "id": 1,
  "name": "John",
  "city": "Pune"
}

---

8. ARRAY OF JSON OBJECTS

Used when multiple records are returned.

Example:
[
  {
    "id": 1,
    "name": "A"
  },
  {
    "id": 2,
    "name": "B"
  }
]

---

9. ENTITY CLASS MAPPING (SPRING BOOT + JPA)

@Entity is used to map Java class to database table.

Example:
@Entity
class Employee {
  int id;
  String fname;
  String lname;
}

This becomes table in database.

---

10. @SPRINGBOOTAPPLICATION (VERY IMPORTANT)

This is the main annotation in Spring Boot.

It is a combination of:

1. @Configuration
2. @ComponentScan
3. @EnableAutoConfiguration

Meaning:
It tells Spring Boot to start configuration, scan components, and auto-configure application.

---

11. POSTMAN (API TESTING TOOL)

Postman is used to test REST APIs.

Uses:
- Testing GET request
- Testing POST request
- Sending JSON data
- Checking response status

---

12. REAL TIME FLOW OF SPRING BOOT APPLICATION

1. Client sends HTTP request
2. Controller receives request
3. Service layer processes logic
4. Repository interacts with database
5. Response returned as JSON

Flow:
Client → Controller → Service → Repository → Database

